<section class="block-section story">
  <span class="section-tag">Story</span>
  <h2>Why this block matters</h2>
  <p class="sub">Last full drafting day. Peer feedback is the rubric-aware kind today, not the evidence-audit kind from Block 6.</p>
  <p>The first 50 minutes is conferencing rotation — Mr. Ignash floats with students who need help on specific sections. The most-flagged weakness across cohorts is the <strong>projections section</strong> (Step 5 of the <a href="/units/unit-2/assessment-landscape-reading/">Landscape Reading</a>) — students default to "everything stays the same in all three scenarios." That's a T/T gate on the rubric. Mr. Ignash will likely camp in the projections section for half the floats.</p>
  <p>The next 25 minutes is structured peer feedback. Unlike Block 6's evidence audit, this round is <strong>rubric-aware</strong> — your peer reviews against the K/U, T/T, and C strands and gives you one specific suggestion per strand. The closing 5 minutes is the final format-choice lock: written, video, or infographic. Format choice doesn't affect strand scores; pick whichever lets your thinking land clearest.</p>
</section>

