<section class="block-section do">
  <span class="section-tag">Do</span>
  <h2>Today's work — choose one path</h2>
  <p class="sub">All four paths end the same: drafted Reading (all 6 components) + peer feedback note. The path is about how you spend the drafting half before the peer feedback round.</p>
  <div class="choice-intro">
    <strong>Learning Intention:</strong> I have a complete draft of the Landscape Reading across all 6 components (biography past + present, projections, recommendations, AI Doc, share-out plan) AND a peer feedback note flagging one specific improvement per rubric strand.
  </div>
  <div class="choice-board">
    <div class="choice">
      <div class="choice-letter">A</div>
      <div class="choice-title">Full work + paired peer feedback (default)</div>
      <div class="choice-detail">Spend the first 50 minutes drafting, then paired peer feedback for 25 minutes using the protocol sheet. Default path for most students. Conferencing rotation is open the whole drafting half.</div>
      <span class="udl-tag">Solo + pairs · Default</span>
    </div>
    <div class="choice">
      <div class="choice-letter">B</div>
      <div class="choice-title">AI Doc + Field Geologist on your riskiest section (stretch)</div>
      <div class="choice-detail">Open the <a href="/ai-partners/field-geologist/">Field Geologist</a>. Describe the riskiest section of your draft (the one you flagged in Block 7's reflection). Ask it to push you on the evidence. Document the full exchange in your <a href="/foundations/ai-documentation-protocol/">AI Documentation Template</a>. Then return to peer feedback.</div>
      <span class="udl-tag">Solo · Stretch</span>
    </div>
    <div class="choice">
      <div class="choice-letter">C</div>
      <div class="choice-title">Self-review against the rubric (choice)</div>
      <div class="choice-detail">Before peer feedback, score your own draft against the rubric. K/U / T/T / C each get a self-band. The point: catch your own gaps before your peer does. Especially useful if peer feedback feels exposing.</div>
      <span class="udl-tag">Solo · Choice</span>
    </div>
    <div class="choice">
      <div class="choice-letter">D</div>
      <div class="choice-title">Audience-voice rewrite (practice)</div>
      <div class="choice-detail">After watching the audience-voice exemplar (Watch card above), pick ONE section of your draft that reads as academic-paper voice. Rewrite it in planning-audience voice. The C-strand gate at 5-6 is the academic-voice trap; this is the targeted practice for moving past it.</div>
      <span class="udl-tag">Solo · Practice</span>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="block-section show">
  <span class="section-tag">Show</span>
  <h2>What you're submitting today</h2>
  <p class="sub">Three components lock today — Components 4 &amp; 5 (T/T) + Component 6 (K/U). After today, K/U and T/T are essentially complete.</p>
  <div class="submission-callout">
    <div class="label">Components 4 + 5 (T/T) + 6 (K/U) + peer feedback note + format choice</div>
    <p>By end of class, in your dossier folder: (1) <strong>Component 4 — future projections</strong>: Step 5, three <em>differentiated</em> scenarios (T/T). (2) <strong>Component 5 — recommendations</strong>: Step 6, 3–5 specific, evidence-anchored, actionable (T/T). (3) <strong>Component 6 — AI Documentation log</strong>: every substantive AI conversation logged with OPVL + "one thing the AI got wrong" (K/U). These three <strong>lock today</strong>. Plus, not strand-marked today: a peer feedback note (one specific suggestion per rubric strand) and your format choice locked (written / video / infographic).</p>
    <a href="#" class="rubric-link">Submit via Google Classroom →</a>
  </div>
  <p class="rubric-meta">
    <strong>Rubric link:</strong> Two of today's components are band-capped watch-outs (see the <a href="/units/unit-2/assessment-landscape-reading/">handout</a>): <strong>Component 4 (projections)</strong> caps at 3-4 T/T if the three scenarios aren't differentiated, and <strong>Component 6 (AI Doc)</strong> scores 1-2 K/U if missing or trivial. After today's locks, only the Block 9 Communication components remain. See the <a href="/foundations/the-rubric/">rubric</a>.
  </p>
</section>

